{"title":"Volatile Fatty Acids (VFA) Time Series (Digesters 1–3)","analysis_comments":"VFAs are very low (generally <~40 mg/L) through mid‑Sep, then rise sharply starting ~20 Sep across all digesters (common-cause event). The 1000 mg/L “stress” threshold is crossed by ~10–12 Oct, and 2000 mg/L “very high” is reached by late Oct for Digesters 2–3 and early Nov for Digester 1.

Peak VFAs occur mid‑Nov: Digester 1 max 4,505 mg/L (18 Nov), Digester 2 max 3,178 mg/L (17 Nov), Digester 3 max 4,268 mg/L (15 Nov). Digester 3 remains >~1,000 mg/L into late Dec and is still ~471 mg/L on 7 Jan, while Digesters 1–2 recover faster (<~300 mg/L by late Dec/early Jan).

This pattern suggests a prolonged imbalance where acid formation exceeded methanogenesis; Digester 3 appears most impacted or slowest to recover (mixing, heating, inhibition, or different feed allocation). Cross-check around late Sep for feed change/FOG, primary vs WAS blend shift, centrate returns, polymer/chemical impacts, or temperature/heating outages.","chart_filename":"vfa_timeseries_1.png","chart_html_filename":"vfa_timeseries_1.html","code_filename":"vfa_timeseries_1.py","data_filename":"vfa_timeseries_1.csv"}

{"title":"Alkalinity Time Series (Digesters 1–3)","analysis_comments":"Alkalinity generally sits in a buffered range (~3,200–3,700 mg/L) through Jun–Aug, then trends downward into late Sep/early Oct, with Digester 1 briefly near the 2,500 mg/L “lower target” (min 2,432 mg/L on 4 Oct). This loss of alkalinity coincides with the onset of rapidly rising VFAs and VFA/Alk ratios, consistent with buffering being consumed by acid accumulation and/or reduced alkalinity generation/addition.

A notable response follows: alkalinity increases sharply in late Oct–mid Nov (especially D1 and D3), exceeding 4,000 mg/L for extended periods; Digester 1 peaks at 4,694 mg/L (17 Nov), Digester 3 peaks 4,565 mg/L (17 Nov). This suggests a corrective operational action (e.g., alkalinity/caustic addition, increased recycle of high-alkalinity streams) during the upset.

By mid‑Dec, alkalinity drops again (Digester 3 lowest 2,373 mg/L on 29 Dec) while its VFAs remain relatively high, helping explain why Digester 3’s VFA/Alk ratio stays elevated longer.","chart_filename":"alkalinity_timeseries_1.png","chart_html_filename":"alkalinity_timeseries_1.html","code_filename":"alkalinity_timeseries_1.py","data_filename":"alkalinity_timeseries_1.csv"}

{"title":"Biogas Production Time Series (Digesters 1–3)","analysis_comments":"Gas production shows a pronounced, synchronized crash beginning late Sep/early Oct, matching the timing of VFA rise and pH decline—strong evidence of methanogenic inhibition/overload rather than a sampling artifact. Approximate minima occur in early Nov: Digester 1 drops to ~528 m³/d (3 Nov), Digester 2 to ~1,107 m³/d (7 Nov), Digester 3 to ~1,884 m³/d (6 Nov). Digester 1’s collapse is most severe relative to its baseline (~5,500–6,300 m³/d).

Recovery is gradual and largely complete by mid‑Dec; by 7 Jan, gas is back near pre-upset levels (D1 ~5,569; D2 ~5,198; D3 ~5,815 m³/d). The timing—gas recovering while VFAs were still elevated—suggests either (a) a portion of VFA converted once inhibition eased, (b) reduced loading plus improved buffering/heating, or (c) measurement/operational changes affecting gas capture.

